&lt;span class="subject"&gt;&lt;a href="/search?l=blink-dev@chromium.org&amp;q=subject:%22Re%5C%3A+%5C%5Bblink%5C-dev%5C%5D+Web%5C-Facing+Change+PSA%5C%3A+InputEvent+types+for+deletion+commands+on+non%5C-collapsed+selections%22&amp;o=newest" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;span itemprop="name"&gt;Re: [blink-dev] Web-Facing Change PSA: InputEvent types for deletion commands on non-collapsed selections&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p class="darkgray font13"&gt;
&lt;span class="sender pipe"&gt;&lt;a href="/search?l=blink-dev@chromium.org&amp;q=from:%22%27Pranav+Modi%27+via+blink%5C-dev%22" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"&gt;&lt;span itemprop="name"&gt;'Pranav Modi' via blink-dev&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="date"&gt;&lt;a href="/search?l=blink-dev@chromium.org&amp;q=date:20260211" rel="nofollow"&gt;Wed, 11 Feb 2026 06:39:42 -0800&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div itemprop="articleBody" class="msgBody"&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;

Doing a compat analysis for this change does not look straightforward to me 
as the change that is being proposed, happens in a specific use-case where 
there is a* modifier+key combination (Ctrl+Backspace, Ctrl+Delete, etc.) *while 
having a non-collapsed selection.
That said, for a site to actually break from this, it would need to:&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;pre&gt;

   1. Listen for beforeinput/input events, 
   2. Specifically branch on inputType === &quot;deleteWordBackward&quot; (or similar 
   granularity types). This condition will be impacted only in case of 
   presence of non-collapsed selection and deletion via modifier keys. 
   3. Not have a handler for deleteContentBackward/deleteContentForward — 
   which they'd already need for plain Backspace/Delete (Any site handling 
   input events for deletion already handles 
   deleteContentBackward/deleteContentForward (since those are what plain 
   Backspace/Delete produce), so receiving these types for Ctrl+Backspace with 
   a selection will naturally fall into existing code paths.). 


As this appears to be rare scenario, *our motivation is to make the event 
spec compliant along with publishing a PSA which should be a sufficient 
enough mitigation*. Also note that this change is behind a runtime flag (
InputEventsDeleteNonCollapsedSelection ), so we can quickly disable it if 
any issues surface post-launch.

